  "final_text": "Snapshot captured. The full JSON is saved at `~/.claude/projects/.../tool-results/bo85mcj66.txt` \u2014 here's the summary:\n\n## Debug snapshot \u2014 NUCLEO-L476RG (probe 066DFF48\u2026, attached without reset)\n\n**Target state:** halted in place, single thread (`main`), executing from flash.\n\n**Core registers:**\n| Reg | Value | |\n|---|---|---|\n| PC | `0x08002B76` | flash, mid-function |\n| LR | `0x08001BE3` | caller in flash (Thumb) |\n| SP/MSP | `0x20017FA8` | main stack, PSP unused (0) |\n| CONTROL | 0 | privileged, MSP |\n| xPSR | `0x61000000` | Thumb state, no active exception (IPSR=0) \u2014 **not faulted** |\n| r0 | `0x2000002C` | SRAM pointer |\n| r3 | `0xFFFFFFFF` | |\n\nFPU present, all FP regs clear; PRIMASK/FAULTMASK/BASEPRI all 0 (interrupts enabled).\n\n**Callstack:**\n- #0 `0x08002b76` \u2014 `??`\n- #1 `0x08001be2` \u2014 `??`\n\n**Disassembly at PC** shows a classic HAL flag-polling loop: load a register through a struct pointer (`[r3, #28]`), AND against a mask, compare, branch back \u2014 the target is busy-waiting on a peripheral status flag (consistent with a `HAL_*` timeout/flag wait), not crashed.\n\n**One caveat:** symbols resolved as `??` even though the descriptor's ELF (`Debug/BLINKY.elf`) was autodiscovered \u2014 the firmware on the board likely doesn't match the built BLINKY ELF (the address layout fits a HAL-based image, but symbol addresses don't line up). If you want named frames, either rebuild/reflash BLINKY or point me at the ELF that's actually on the board and I'll re-run `callstack --full`."
}